!! What it does

llm help provides a self-discoverable, hierarchical documentation system that LLMs navigate via a single MCP tool `llm_help`. Instead of loading all documentation upfront, the LLM browses a tree of help pages level by level, reading only what it needs for the current task.

!! Features

* ''Hierarchical navigation'' -- help pages organized in a tree of any depth, navigated level by level
* ''Dynamic content'' -- pages are wikitext rendered at call time, pulling live data from the wiki (e.g., typed schemas, existing instances)
* ''Context-aware'' -- pages can be scoped to specific contexts (e.g., an appify app) via set-intersection filtering
* ''Multi-path mounting'' -- same page reachable from multiple paths in the tree via space-separated `llm-help-path` values
* ''Plugin-extensible'' -- any plugin contributes help pages by tagging tiddlers with `$:/tags/rimir/llm-help/page`
* ''User shortcuts'' -- users add quick-reference help pages via the settings UI for common tasks or failing use cases
* ''Help browser'' -- settings tab lets users see and navigate the exact same tree the LLM sees

!! Prerequisites

* [[$:/plugins/rimir/llm-connect]] -- provides the MCP tool infrastructure
* [[$:/plugins/rimir/theme]] -- provides UI styling classes

!! Quick start

# Install the plugin (requires llm-connect and theme)
# The `llm_help` tool automatically appears in the llm-connect tool list
# Open Settings > LLM Help to browse the help tree
# Other plugins (e.g., orga) contribute domain-specific help pages automatically

!! How the LLM uses it

```
llm_help()                         → see top-level topics
llm_help("data-model")             → navigate into data model docs
llm_help("data-model/person")      → read person schema (dynamic)
llm_help("data-model/person/create") → step-by-step creation guide
```

Each response includes subtopic listings with descriptions, so the LLM autonomously decides where to navigate based on the task at hand.

